ced throughout Europe, especially in Scandinavia in the form  <b>Birgit</b> , as the name of the patron saint of Sweden (  1304–73 ). She was a noblewoman of Irish stock who, after the death of her husband, founded an order of nuns, the Bridgettines. Later she went to Rome and attempted to introduce religious reforms there."],"variants":[{"name":"Bridgid","meanings":["Anglicized form of Gaelic Brighid (pronounced ‘breed’); . This was the name of an ancient Celtic goddess, which in Gaulish would have been <i>Brigindos</i>, meaning ‘the exalted one’.  St Brigid  of Kildare (  <i>c.</i>450– <i>c.</i>525 ) is one of the patron saints of Ireland. Very few facts are known about her life. She founded a religious house for women at Kildare, and is said to be have been buried at Downpatrick, where  St Patrick  and  St Columba  were also buried. Many of the stories of miracles told about  St Brigid  seem to be Christianized versions of pagan legends concerning the goddess. The popularity of the name was further reinforced throughout Europe, especially in Scandinavia in the form  <b>Birgit</b> , as the name of the patron saint of Sweden (  1304–73 ). She was a noblewoman of Irish stock who, after the death of her husband, founded an order of nuns, the Bridgettines. Later she went to Rome and attempted to introduce religious reforms there."]},{"name":"Bridgit","meanings":["Anglicized form of Gaelic Brighid (pronounced ‘breed’); . This was the name of an ancient Celtic goddess, which in Gaulish would have been <i>Brigindos</i>, meaning ‘the exalted one’.  St Brigid  of Kildare (  <i>c.</i>450– <i>c.</i>525 ) is one of the patron saints of Ireland. Very few facts are known about her life. She founded a religious house for women at Kildare, and is said to be have been buried at Downpatrick, where  St Patrick  and  St Columba  were also buried. Many of the stories of miracles told about  St Brigid  seem to be Christianized versions of pagan legends concerning the goddess. The popularity of the name was further reinforced throughout Europe, especially in Scandinavia in the form  <b>Birgit</b> , as the name of the patron saint of Sweden (  1304–73 ). She was a noblewoman of Irish stock who, after the death of her husband, founded an order of nuns, the Bridgettines. Later she went to Rome and attempted to introduce religious reforms there."]},{"name":"Brigid","meanings":["Traditional name meaning ‘the exalted one’.  See  <b>Bridget</b>   ."]},{"name":"Brigit","meanings":["Traditional name meaning ‘the exalted one’.  See  <b>Bridget</b>   ."]},{"name":"Brighid","meanings":["Traditional name meaning ‘the exalted one’.  See  <b>Bridget</b>   ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Bridget Hunterston was born about 1215, in Europe as the daughter of Alexander Hunterston. She had at least 2 sons with Ralph Baskerville."},"et":{"about 1215–":"umbes 1215–Surnud","1215–Female":"1215–Surnud","1200–Male":"1200–Surnud","1230–Male":"1230–Surnud","1240–Male":"1240–Surnud","1190–Male":"1190–Surnud","1190":"1190","ABT 1240":"umbes 1240","1215":"1215","about 1215":"umbes 1215","1200":"1200","1230":"1230","1240":"1240","Europe":"Europe","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1215–":"noin 1215–Kuollut","1215–Female":"1215–Kuollut","1200–Male":"1200–Kuollut","1230–Male":"1230–Kuollut","1240–Male":"1240–Kuollut","1190–Male":"1190–Kuollut","1190":"1190","ABT 1240":"noin 1240","1215":"1215","about 1215":"noin 1215","1200":"1200","1230":"1230","1240":"1240","Europe":"Europe","England, United Kingdom":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1215–":"environ 1215–Décédée","1215–Female":"1215–Décédée","1200–Male":"1200–Décédé","1230–Male":"1230–Décédé","1240–Male":"1240–Décédé","1190–Male":"1190–Décédé","1190":"1190","ABT 1240":"environ 1240","1215":"1215","about 1215":"environ 1215","1200":"1200","1230":"1230","1240":"1240","Europe":"Europe","England, United Kingdom":"Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Bridget Hunterston est née environ 1215, 